Note:
Runa Standard Library: Fourier Transform and Signal Processing

High-level API for Fourier transforms that delegates to the high-performance FFT engine.
This provides the user-friendly interface while the engine handles computation.
:End Note

Import "math/core" as Core
Import "math/complex" as Complex
Import "math/engine/fourier/fft" as FFTEngine

Note: Type Definitions
Type Signal is List[Number]
Type ComplexSignal is List[Complex.ComplexNumber]
Type FrequencySpectrum is List[Complex.ComplexNumber]

Note: Basic Fourier Transform API
Process called "fft" that takes signal as Signal returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: Fast Fourier Transform with automatic real-to-complex conversion
    Return FFTEngine.real_fft_engine with signal as signal

Process called "ifft" that takes spectrum as ComplexSignal returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: Inverse Fast Fourier Transform
    Return FFTEngine.ifft_engine with spectrum as spectrum

Process called "fft_complex" that takes signal as ComplexSignal returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: FFT for complex-valued signals
    Return FFTEngine.fft_radix2_engine with signal as signal

Process called "dft" that takes signal as Signal returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: Discrete Fourier Transform (direct computation)
    Let complex_signal be to_complex_signal with signal as signal
    Return FFTEngine.dft_engine with signal as complex_signal

Note: Real-valued signal optimizations
Process called "real_fft" that takes signal as Signal returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: Optimized FFT for real signals (returns only positive frequencies)
    Return FFTEngine.real_fft_engine with signal as signal

Process called "rfft" that takes signal as Signal returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: Alias for real_fft
    Return real_fft with signal as signal

Process called "irfft" that takes spectrum as ComplexSignal and n as Integer returns Signal:
    Note: Inverse real FFT
    Let full_spectrum be reconstruct_full_spectrum with half_spectrum as spectrum and n as n
    Let complex_result be FFTEngine.ifft_engine with spectrum as full_spectrum
    Return extract_real_part with complex_signal as complex_result

Note: 2D Fourier Transforms
Process called "fft_2d" that takes matrix as List[List[Number]] returns List[List[Complex.ComplexNumber]]:
    Note: 2D FFT for images and matrices
    Let complex_matrix be to_complex_matrix with matrix as matrix
    Return FFTEngine.fft_2d_engine with matrix as complex_matrix

Process called "ifft_2d" that takes spectrum as List[List[Complex.ComplexNumber]] returns List[List[Complex.ComplexNumber]]:
    Note: 2D inverse FFT
    Note: Apply 1D IFFT to each row, then each column
    Let row_transformed be list containing
    For each row in spectrum:
    Add FFTEngine.ifft_engine with spectrum as row to row_transformed Note: Transpose and transform columns
    Let transposed be transpose_matrix with matrix as row_transformed
    Let col_transformed be list containing
    For each col in transposed:
    Add FFTEngine.ifft_engine with spectrum as col to col_transformed Return transpose_matrix with matrix as col_transformed

Note: Signal processing operations
Process called "convolution" that takes signal1 as Signal and signal2 as Signal returns Signal:
    Note: Fast convolution using FFT
    Return FFTEngine.convolution_fft_engine with signal1 as signal1 and signal2 as signal2

Process called "correlation" that takes signal1 as Signal and signal2 as Signal returns Signal:
    Note: Cross-correlation using FFT
    Return FFTEngine.cross_correlation_engine with signal1 as signal1 and signal2 as signal2

Process called "autocorrelation" that takes signal as Signal returns Signal:
    Note: Auto-correlation
    Return correlation with signal1 as signal and signal2 as signal

Note: Spectral analysis
Process called "power_spectrum" that takes signal as Signal and sample_rate as Number returns Signal:
    Note: Compute power spectral density
    Return FFTEngine.power_spectral_density_engine with signal as signal and sample_rate as sample_rate

Process called "magnitude_spectrum" that takes signal as Signal returns Signal:
    Note: Magnitude spectrum from FFT
    Let spectrum be fft with signal as signal
    Let magnitudes be list containing
    For each value in spectrum:
    Add Complex.magnitude with z as value to magnitudes
    Return magnitudes

Process called "phase_spectrum" that takes signal as Signal returns Signal:
    Note: Phase spectrum from FFT
    Let spectrum be fft with signal as signal
    Let phases be list containing
    For each value in spectrum:
    Add Complex.phase with z as value to phases
    Return phases

Process called "spectrogram" that takes signal as Signal and window_size as Integer and overlap as Integer returns List[List[Number]]:
    Note: Short-time Fourier transform for time-frequency analysis
    Let hop_size be window_size - overlap
    Let n_windows be (signal.length - overlap) divided by hop_size
    Let spectrogram be list containing For i from 0 to (n_windows - 1):
    Let start be i multiplied by hop_size
    Let end be Math.min with a as (start + window_size) and b as signal.length
    Let window be extract_slice with signal as signal and start as start and end as end Note: Apply window function and compute FFT
    Let windowed be apply_hamming_window with signal as window
    Let spectrum be magnitude_spectrum with signal as windowed
    Add spectrum to spectrogram Return spectrogram

Note: Window functions
Process called "hamming_window" that takes length as Integer returns Signal:
    Note: Hamming window function
    Let window be list containing
    For i from 0 to (length - 1):
    Let value be 0.54 - 0.46 multiplied by (Core.cos with angle as (2.0 multiplied by Core.pi multiplied by i divided by (length - 1)))
    Add value to window
    Return window

Process called "hanning_window" that takes length as Integer returns Signal:
    Note: Hanning window function
    Let window be list containing
    For i from 0 to (length - 1):
    Let value be 0.5 - 0.5 multiplied by (Core.cos with angle as (2.0 multiplied by Core.pi multiplied by i divided by (length - 1)))
    Add value to window
    Return window

Process called "blackman_window" that takes length as Integer returns Signal:
    Note: Blackman window function
    Let window be list containing
    For i from 0 to (length - 1):
    Let a0 be 0.42
    Let a1 be 0.5
    Let a2 be 0.08
    Let angle1 be 2.0 multiplied by Core.pi multiplied by i divided by (length - 1)
    Let angle2 be 4.0 multiplied by Core.pi multiplied by i divided by (length - 1)
    Let value be a0 - a1 multiplied by (Core.cos with angle as angle1) + a2 multiplied by (Core.cos with angle as angle2)
    Add value to window
    Return window

Process called "apply_hamming_window" that takes signal as Signal returns Signal:
    Note: Apply Hamming window to signal
    Let window be hamming_window with length as signal.length
    Let windowed be list containing
    For i from 0 to (signal.length - 1):
    Add signal[i] multiplied by window[i] to windowed
    Return windowed

Note: Frequency analysis utilities
Process called "frequency_bins" that takes n_samples as Integer and sample_rate as Number returns Signal:
    Note: Generate frequency bins for FFT output
    Let bins be list containing
    For i from 0 to (n_samples divided by 2):
    Let freq be i multiplied by sample_rate divided by n_samples
    Add freq to bins
    Return bins

Process called "find_peak_frequency" that takes signal as Signal and sample_rate as Number returns Number:
    Note: Find dominant frequency in signal
    Let spectrum be magnitude_spectrum with signal as signal
    Let max_magnitude be 0.0
    Let peak_index be 0 For i from 0 to (spectrum.length - 1):
    If spectrum[i] is greater than max_magnitude:
    Set max_magnitude to spectrum[i]
    Set peak_index to i Return peak_index multiplied by sample_rate divided by (2 multiplied by spectrum.length)

Note: Utility functions
Process called "to_complex_signal" that takes signal as Signal returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: Convert real signal to complex
    Let complex_signal be list containing
    For each value in signal:
    Add Complex.create_complex with real as value and imaginary as 0.0 to complex_signal
    Return complex_signal

Process called "to_complex_matrix" that takes matrix as List[List[Number]] returns List[List[Complex.ComplexNumber]]:
    Note: Convert real matrix to complex
    Let complex_matrix be list containing
    For each row in matrix:
    Let complex_row be list containing
    For each value in row:
    Add Complex.create_complex with real as value and imaginary as 0.0 to complex_row
    Add complex_row to complex_matrix
    Return complex_matrix

Process called "extract_real_part" that takes complex_signal as ComplexSignal returns Signal:
    Note: Extract real part from complex signal
    Let real_signal be list containing
    For each value in complex_signal:
    Add value.real to real_signal
    Return real_signal

Process called "reconstruct_full_spectrum" that takes half_spectrum as ComplexSignal and n as Integer returns ComplexSignal:
    Note: Reconstruct full spectrum from half spectrum (for real signals)
    Let full_spectrum be list containing Note: Add positive frequencies
    For each value in half_spectrum:
    Add value to full_spectrum Note: Add negative frequencies (conjugate symmetry)
    For i from (half_spectrum.length - 2) down to 1:
    Add Complex.conjugate with z as half_spectrum[i] to full_spectrum Return full_spectrum

Process called "transpose_matrix" that takes matrix as List[List[Complex.ComplexNumber]] returns List[List[Complex.ComplexNumber]]:
    Note: Transpose complex matrix
    Let rows be matrix.length
    Let cols be matrix[0].length
    Let transposed be list containing For j from 0 to (cols - 1):
    Let new_row be list containing
    For i from 0 to (rows - 1):
    Add matrix[i][j] to new_row
    Add new_row to transposed Return transposed

Process called "extract_slice" that takes signal as Signal and start as Integer and end as Integer returns Signal:
    Note: Extract slice from signal
    Let slice be list containing
    For i from start to (end - 1):
    Add signal[i] to slice
    Return slice